{"key":"post-11605574","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11605574</id>\n<content>&lt;br /&gt;Experimentation doesn't mean repeating the same failed experiment of trying to run a car on four square wheels over and over again.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A quick search will reveal the hundred or so before you who have tried this and failed.&amp;nbsp; A fact of physics is that water doesn't exist in a liquid state at atmospheric pressure, above 212F/100C.&amp;nbsp; Another fact is that mason jars seal in vacuum, not pressure.&amp;nbsp; If your water turns to steam at 100C, it's all going to be lost, and the only physical way your substrate can be heated to 212F/100C is for all the water to be completely gone.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Use a steam sterilizer or find a different hobby.&amp;nbsp; There's plenty to experiment on without trying to defy the laws of gravity and physics.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Fractional sterilization fails more than half of the time, when used with mushroom growing.&amp;nbsp; If someone is satisfied with a fifty percent failure rate, they're going to be spending more on grains than a pressure cooker would cost after the first three or four attempts.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11605620</next>\n<prev>11605548</prev>\n<first>11604701</first>\n<last>11616689</last>\n<when>1260235285</when>\n<utime>12/08/09 03:21 AM</utime>\n</post>"}